<br>
I'm currently trying to find a way to get an isdn line to work with a friends setup so would be interested to hear anyones suggestion. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/umalldar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Malldar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Wandering Knight</span><br>  Posts: 113<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/19/02 6:03:46 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=15752.topic&index=39>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: dsl</span><hr size=1> One modem :) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ueqjonze.showPublicProfile?language=EN>eqjonze</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Blessed Protector</span><br>  Posts: 366<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/19/02 9:32:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=15752.topic&index=40>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: cable</span><hr size=1> I use cable.  One NIC in each computer connected to a 'hub' that connects to my cable modem.  I pay for an extra IP address for the other computer.  Works great. <p><b>Jonze</b> 57 Paladin
<br><a href="http://www.eqwhitewind.com"> White Wind on Drinal
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ucaladel.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Caladel</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Holy Defender</span><br>  Posts: 649<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/19/02 4:45:00 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=15752.topic&index=41>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: cable</span><hr size=1> My personal setup is a dedicated gateway using ip masqurading. Its built out of old spare parts that were collecting dust for 5-10 years so it cost almost nothign to put it together. You barely need any processing power for a gateway so that old junk has a purpose again hehe. From that i just have a 'dumb' hub connecting all the other computers in my house.<br>
<br>
There are a few issues using ip masqurading but generally it works very well. The issues stem from programs used on the internal network that use dedicated ports. You can get arround issues like this with port redirecting on your gateway, but cant solve every problem. IE you couldnt run 2 httpservers on port 80 on seperate computers behind the gateway. <br>
<br>
Err, ya and for those who dont know ip masqurading refers to using 1 real ip address for your entire network. The comptuers on your internal network all have a unique ip address, but its not a real address as far as the outside world is concerned. Its only real on your internal network, all access with the outside world will be done through your 1 real ip address. As far as the outside world is conerned all the requests are coming from that 1 gateway computer and the computers on your internal network dont exist.<br>
<br>
There are a few small advantages and disadvantages to using this method. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uthaedson.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Thaedson</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Noble Squire</span><br>  Posts: 21<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/20/02 6:35:27 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=15752.topic&index=42>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: cable</span><hr size=1> Use a cable modem hooked up to a Linksys Router.  Can hook up five computers to this system. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uromidar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Romidar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='filter:glow(color=#0000ff,strength=2);width:100%'>Knight of the Truthbringer</span></span><br>  Posts: 75<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/20/02 7:51:36 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=15752.topic&index=43>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.stny.rr.com/drhager/romface.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: cable</span><hr size=1> I'm also using a linksys (wireless) router with cable modem and have 4 computers running at once. Three of them are running EQ (my wifes, my main system and my 2box druid transportation); the fourth is running my work laptop which also doubles as an information resource.<br>
<br>
The only time I notice performance issues tend to be on zoning. My main system (P4, 1.4 ghz) zones in about half the time as my old system (p2 400 Mhz), but when the old system finishes zoning I get a 1 or 2 second pause on my new system. Other than that, they all speed along nicely.<br>
<br>
